{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17489655","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17489655"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T04:25:00+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T04:25:00+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"712"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"712","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/712"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.3,0.09,0.29,0.01,0.32]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"712"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114514"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"712","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/712"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"712"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96515"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1177"},{"type":"tags","id":"2047"},{"type":"tags","id":"2436"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"4965"},{"type":"tags","id":"4985"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"9644"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11634"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2312"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2723"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9224"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13824"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14635"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18503"},{"type":"contributions","id":"38972"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40217"},{"type":"contributions","id":"48050"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114514","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/114514"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 52-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a two-month history of increasing tiredness. She has no other symptoms. She had a Mirena intrauterine device (IUD) inserted for heavy menstrual bleeding four years ago, and reports this has been working well for her. She has no other significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. She is a lifetime non-smoker, drinks small amounts of alcohol at social occasions only and eats a normal, well-balanced diet. She is of Greek heritage.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Her physical examination is unremarkable. Her laboratory investigations show:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHaemoglobin 93 g/L (115-155)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPCV 0.31 L/L (0.35-0.45)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMCV 79.7 fl (80-98)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMCH 24.2 pg (27-33)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMCHC 304 g/L (310-360)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ERDW 14.3% (12-15)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPlatelets 438 x10\u003Csup\u003E9\u003C/sup\u003E (150 - 450)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhite Cell Count 6.52 x10\u003Csup\u003E9\u003C/sup\u003E/L (4.00 - 11.0)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ENeutrophils 4.36 x10\u003Csup\u003E9\u003C/sup\u003E/L (1.80 - 7.50)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELymphocytes 1.59 x10\u003Csup\u003E9\u003C/sup\u003E/L (1.50 - 3.50)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMonocytes 0.35 x10\u003Csup\u003E9\u003C/sup\u003E/L (0.20 - 0.80)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EEosinophils 0.20 x10\u003Csup\u003E9\u003C/sup\u003E/L (0.02 - 0.50)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBasophils 0.02 x10\u003Csup\u003E9\u003C/sup\u003E/L (\u0026lt; 0.11)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFerritin 10 ug/L (15-250)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIron 4 umol/L (8-30)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETransferrin 3.04 g/L (2.00-4.00)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETransferrin Saturation 5 % (10-35)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most important potential diagnosis to consider?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Thalassaemia minor","Heavy menstrual bleeding","Carcinoma of the caecum","Dietary vitamin B12 deficiency","Dietary iron deficiency"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with fatigue and laboratory evidence of a hypochromic, microcytic anaemia with iron deficiency. Given her age and lack of overt bleeding, this presentation raises concern for an occult source of chronic blood loss, most commonly from the gastrointestinal tract.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECarcinoma of the caecum\u003C/strong\u003E is the most likely diagnosis in this scenario. Right-sided colon cancers, such as those in the caecum, often present with iron deficiency anaemia due to chronic, occult blood loss without visible bleeding. The patient\u0027s age (52 years) puts her at increased risk for colorectal cancer, and the absence of other obvious causes for her anaemia makes this diagnosis highly suspicious.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHeavy menstrual bleeding\u003C/strong\u003E would have been a likely cause of anaemia before the Mirena IUD insertion. However, hormonal IUDs typically lead to a significant reduction or cessation of menstrual bleeding, making this an unlikely cause of her current anaemia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThalassaemia minor\u003C/strong\u003E, while an important differential diagnosis especially considering her Greek heritage, is less likely in this case. Thalassaemia is typically diagnosed earlier in life and would not explain the new onset of anaemia with clear iron deficiency.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDietary vitamin B12 deficiency\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect as it typically presents with a hyperchromic, macrocytic anaemia, not the hypochromic, microcytic picture seen here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDietary iron deficiency\u003C/strong\u003E is unlikely given that the patient reports eating a well-balanced diet. Moreover, in the absence of regular blood loss (which is unlikely with a Mirena IUD in place), dietary factors alone rarely cause significant iron deficiency anaemia in adults.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EGiven these findings, the patient should urgently undergo endoscopy and colonoscopy to investigate for a gastrointestinal source of bleeding, particularly colorectal cancer. Concurrently, treatment for her iron deficiency anaemia should be initiated. This case underscores the importance of thoroughly investigating iron deficiency anaemia in older adults, even in the absence of overt gastrointestinal symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["An older individual presenting with iron deficiency anaemia needs to be investigated for bowel cancer with endoscopy and colonoscopy.","Iron deficiency anaemia causes a hypochromic microcytic anaemia."],"references":["Doust J. Diagnostic and management strategies for anaemia in adults. Aust Fam Physician. 2003 Nov;32(11):889-94. Available at: https://www.racgp.org.au/afpbackissues/2003/200311/20031101doust.pdf.","Raje D, Mukhtar H, Oshowo A, Ingham Clark C. What proportion of patients referred to secondary care with iron deficiency anemia have colon cancer? Dis Colon Rectum. 2007 Aug;50(8):1211-4. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/17587088/","Lopez A, Cacoub P, Macdougall IC, et al. Iron deficiency anaemia. Lancet 2016; 387: 907\u201316. Available at: https://www.thelancet.com/journals/lancet/article/PIIS0140-6736(15)60865-0/abstract"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96515"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"712"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96515","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/96515"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-17T10:50:10+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-17T10:51:01+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"712"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114514"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing information